# Release notes

Do not maintain a static `RELEASE_NOTES.md` file. Generate release notes on demand when preparing a release.

## Version

Read the current version from `pyproject.toml` (`[project] version = "x.y.z"`).

Bump version per semantic versioning:
- **Major (x.0.0)** — breaking changes, major auth/architectural shifts
- **Minor (0.y.0)** — new features, non-breaking enhancements
- **Patch (0.0.z)** — bug fixes, documentation, internal changes

## Format

```
# Release v<version>

<One-liner summary of the release. Keep it to one sentence.>

## New Features

- **Feature title** — concise description with key detail. (#PR)

## Fixes

- **Bug title** — concise description with root cause / user impact. (#PR)

## Internal

- Changes that don't affect the user-facing API. (#PR)

---

**Full Changelog**: https://github.com/leshchenko1979/fast-mcp-telegram/compare/<prev-tag>...v<version>
```

## How to generate

1. **Version** — read from `pyproject.toml`, bump as needed
2. **PRs** — collect merged PRs since last tag:
   ```bash
   gh pr list --state merged --base master --json number,title,mergedAt,body --limit 30
   ```
   Or use `git log <prev-tag>..HEAD --oneline --no-decorate`
3. **Categorise** — split into New Features / Fixes / Internal:
   - `feat:` or feature PRs → New Features
   - `fix:` → Fixes
   - `chore:`, `docs:`, `refactor:`, `style:`, `test:` → Internal
   - `security:` → Fixes (label as security)
4. **Summarise** — one line per item with `(#PR_NUMBER)` reference. Focus on user-visible impact, not implementation details
5. **Tag** — create and push the tag:
   ```bash
   git tag -a v<version> -m "Release v<version>"
   git push origin v<version>
   ```
6. **GitHub Release** — create via `gh release create v<version> --title "Release v<version>" --notes-file <notes.md>`
7. **Announce** — post to Telegram (project group `fast-mcp-telegram`) with a summary

